segments.text: sort of Pacific-wide, caused by things which occurred out in the Pacific when tape number two ran out suddenly.
We were talking about a drought wide in the West caused possibly by occurrences out in the Pacific when tape ran out on site number two.
And then I'll save that second side of the tape.
I'll come back up here Monday afternoon.
Okay, you will come back Monday afternoon?
Yes, I sure will.
I'm going to make sure that's right.
Yes, it sure is right.
Now, we were really talking about drought conditions.
Oh, yeah.
Are you on yet or not?
I'm on.
All right.
What I was going to say was that this is a fairly rare event
apparently, in essentially a climatological sense.
It's either something that's occurred about once in the past century or maybe twice in the past century.
So it's worth documenting.
And I made some tentative sort of gestures to try and get some special observations made to essentially find out what was happening in the ocean under these unusual conditions.
And I couldn't find anybody.
who has had the ability or capability to do it, because everybody's committed to other programs.
And this, I think, is very tragic in a way, that here's a good sort of scientific problem, and it has its practical aspects too, and yet you couldn't do anything about it.
You know, as a matter of fact, people now are talking about more and more trying to tie together the work of the atmosphere and the work of the ocean.
But it seems almost as if the departments are dividing whether they're coming closer together on these kinds of problems.
Well, I don't see too many indications of them getting closer together.
There is some interest.

at the moment of some closer cooperation between what is called the Department of Atmospheric Sciences and Oceanography, but I think it just means that each will continue to do what it believes is its mission and they may get together now and again, not really a joint activity.
And this is, I think it's most unfortunate because
I don't think it's entirely a prejudiced point of view, but I think many of the meteorological events are, in effect, if not initiated, dominated by ocean conditions rather than the other way around.
If we want to look at long-term, large-scale forecasting and so on, there's got to be more

attention played to the characteristics of the ocean and there are some programs in other countries where there has been a much closer integration of the atmospheric and marine things and that's particularly true in Japan where one of the major
oceanographic activities in Japan has been the meteorological service.
But in this country it's traditionally been very, very difficult to get any sort of participation by the meteorologist as such in kind of oceanographic things.
Now there are some exceptions, but the exceptions are
are, in a sense, so few that they're kind of conspicuous.
I ran across his name today.
Nehmias is one person who has attempted to do this.
Dr. Bjorkness at UCLA.
But they're dealing more on a kind of a, almost a kind of climatic study type thing.
Now, I have a series of questions, really, about, again, about government participation in the early organization of oceanography.
Are there any congressmen or senators or administrations you would like to cite who forwarded oceanography as an academic discipline in the 40s and the 50s?
Well, I think the...

outstanding example is Senator Magnuson, who has for a number of years been very much involved with these things and is still very much involved, not just as a representative of our state, but as he's concerned about this national program.
He is the only one, and I've had only very little
limited set of contacts with him, but I've over the years gone by have had a fair amount of contact with his some of his staff, but not with in my case with any any others at all.
We've never had a

congressman from the state of Washington I don't think that has been interested and senator Jackson's interests have always been in other in other fields so professor the senator Magnuson is is the to my mind the number one here now if you talk to people from other parts of the country I'm sure you get other no he's always cited
The only other exception is that frequently Vice President Humphrey is cited in Washington for offering special aid at one time or another.

Well, he did, and particularly during this phase of the Stratton Commission, that's not his technical name, and so on, and he was very much involved in this, and of course we have on the campus here Professor Edward Wank, who's
was one of the key people, not in the Stratton Commission, but in the Marine Council, which functioned at the same time as him.
Is Ed Wink on the campus now?
Do you want this on the tape?
Yes.
I'm not sure whether he's physically on the campus as of today or so, because he's been on a sabbatical leave this past year, but he has an appointment in engineering on the campus here, yeah.
So he was supposed to be back this month, but I'm not sure whether he's back or not.
We can certainly check up next week.
I followed him from D.C. and halfway across the country trying to get in to see him.
He's a hard man to get to see.
Now, there's also been suggested that really the sudden boom in oceanography that occurs in the 50s comes as a result of the IGY activities.
Would you agree with that?
Well, I think IGY marked a change here in that this was, I think it's fair to say, about the first time that there had ever been
funds available to a number of institutions for essentially a planned program of events.
And I think part of the reason for some of the boom that followed that and the

Indian Ocean Expedition was a case in point here, was the fact that there was a recognition on the part of the government that maybe science was a useful kind of diplomatic tool here, because this opened up
communications with Russia, at least in some areas, and it turned out that oceanography was one of the better in the sense of exchange of information and sort of cooperation.
Now under IGY there was supposed to be an effect of complete exchange, but it did not work at all because this represented the beginning of the space program and that sort of
close, but it did keep the communications open in oceanography.
And I am told that this is part of the reason why the decision was made to go with this Indian Ocean expedition, was to keep this kind of international contacts open.
And the Indian Ocean was picked as essentially being neutral territory.
And I think it has.
And ever since that time, I think in oceanography, there has been a reasonable set of contacts between the Russian and American oceanographers.
Now, it's not always what you'd like it to be, but at least the channels are open, if not very large.
So I think it was a kind of political as much.
The political implications may have essentially had an important place here.
That's what I'm trying to say.
It was not just the arguments of the scientists or anything that did this.
There was more to it than that.
There was a feeling.
I don't know how widely it was felt.
I sort of felt this way for a while.
we might be, it might be possible and so on for the, as part of a kind of a national policy to divert some of the effort that went into the space program as it was being sort of phased down into the
put me into the sea, but that never happened.

As a matter of fact, I anticipate my next question is that an assumption, at least on part of the oceanographers, was exactly what you pointed out, that as space developed, then so would the ocean, too.
Now, it didn't occur, obviously, as you pointed out.
Now oceanographers are saying the 70s may be the decades of the ocean because of mariculture, aquaculture,
mining for magnesium nodules and these sorts of things.
Manganese.
Manganese, I'm sorry.
Manganese nodules.
What are your feelings on that?
Well, there's some curious things here which I think to a scientist are hard to rationalize, or maybe to anybody to rationalize, that there's obviously
these things carry with them more than a kind of a rational approach.
There's a question of people just getting interested in doing things, becoming aware of them.
And also, it may be that certain things will be done not for economic justification,
is a question of national prestige or turn it around because we want to help other countries or something.
In other words, there's a variety of sort of elements involved here.
I am not inspired by the aquaculture, mariculture thing, because I really don't see any great merit in it.
But I will not say that there may not be major developments in this area.
But it doesn't seem to me as a particularly
major sort of enterprise.
The reason is that it is, in effect, to cost labor and materials expensive.
At the present time, the only possibilities in this area are for essentially very high-priced products.
Now, this may be perfectly valid in a way,
It doesn't really answer the question of feeding large numbers of people.
My feeling is I'll let other people worry about these things.
The manganese nodule thing is, again, I think very interesting in the way in that almost all of the
uses of marine resources have developed out of a kind of traditional pattern over a fairly lengthy period of time, fishing as a case in point.
But even in the petroleum business, the progress of the extension of this drilling and wells and recovery of petroleum and natural gas from beneath the seashore
moved gradually from on land into very shallow water and then into deeper and deeper water so they could, in a sense, feel their way.
This manganese nodules problem is to me interesting because of the fact that there was no technology in existence that could be modified or extended.
It was a completely new kind of enterprise and it involved
very major investment of capital with no assurance that it would work.
And if they did work, whether it was economically feasible.
And we don't know the answers to that.
And I don't think we're going to know for some years yet.
I think it's a good sort of thing to do, but it's
But it is a sort of an interesting example of something that's more or less unique, I think.
And it may not pay off for a long, long time.
So you don't see these ideas attracting a vast amount of money, let's say, for the oceanography?
No, no.
This is what I tried to hedge on when I first started my comments here, that just interest may
promote some of these things because people think it's interesting or think it's fun to do these sort of things.
And, you know, who made the decision on the part of these companies that have invested large amounts of money in this manganese thing and, you know, what really tipped the scales
they decided to go ahead with it.
I don't think you can say it's really on the basis of rational analysis.
It's just somebody got curious and interested.
Now, you had pointed out, again another question I wanted to ask, that the IGY had spurred international cooperation.

Some people are arguing now in terms of political geography that the sort of division up of the ocean with 200-mile limits, underdeveloped countries arguing that they're being exploited by oceanographers or oceanographic research at least, and international conferences of the sea will push American oceanography and other oceanographic research back into shore, away from the outer ocean, and complicate it for people in your profession.
Would you agree with those sort of series of assumptions?

Well, I think yes and no, but in that there are again sort of strange differences between the way in which people regard various parts of planet Earth here that have become so much a part of our kind of culture, they don't stop and realize that
that there have been restraints in effect on what you can do on land for a long, long time here because of the whole concept of property rights.
The atmosphere has another set of things that go with it.
But even today, a country or even an individual has certain rights to the air column immediately over a piece of real estate.
No airplanes are allowed to fly over a foreign area without permission from that particular country.

And yet with the sea, because of different attitudes and traditions, we have this quite different picture that we used to call freedom of the seas and so on, that anybody could go anywhere, anytime, and do anything.

Also, what was a very sort of arbitrary thing, although I think it had its basis in a very realistic sort of an approach of the territorial sea and the three mile limit as it's usually identified, although it was not always three miles.
But this whole business of how do you deal with the ocean and a sense of kind of ownership and so on,
certainly unresolved, and what's happening, as you indicated a moment ago, is that each coastal country is extending its interests seaward, and then the view of the

underdeveloped countries and the landlocked countries and so on, that a large part of the ocean should never come under any individual country's control, but somehow or other ought to be for the benefit of all.
And this is, as you are well aware, a subject of very hot debate here.
There are
fairly strong arguments in favor of some kind of dividing up of the ocean.
Now, it could be divided up so that, say, the United Nations owns most of it.
But if you remember your historical precedents, all sorts of interesting things happened at

in England in particular, in what they call the enclosure acts, that when they went away from the concept of the common to essentially individual property rights, that the productivity of agriculture increased just tremendously under this change.
It's often
Cited as an example of horrible social injustice, but apparently this is altogether true.
Apparently the poor people, in many cases, profited greatly from the enclosures.
And I'm just out of reasoning by analogy here, but I think this fishery business, if there is some sense of ownership, then it's to your advantage to try and protect that.
Whereas if it doesn't belong to anybody, they're just out there for whoever wants to take them and so on.
The whales are probably the most newsworthy example of this at the moment.

They feel, at the moment, that this 200-mile Fishery Conservation and Management Act will, in effect, have a very beneficial effect on, not just in the economic sense of how it may affect the fishermen of the United States and so on, but actually in the long-term kind of management of this resource for the benefit of everybody.
I just don't know.

I'm not too involved emotionally in this business about freedom of scientific research, although some of my peers are concerned in that I think there are many examples of where this is actually being abused in one way or another.
We have a right to get slapped a little bit on it.
This again gets you back into the subject that's come up several times of what is research and what isn't here, and that what is a research vessel and what isn't.
And this is being debated because of the
The vessels operated by the oil companies and some of these geophysical exploration companies want to call themselves research vessels.
So from an outsider's point of view, what's the difference between a vessel operated by the University of Washington and one operated by us all?
It's the same way our vessel, as far as a foreign country is concerned, is still looked on as a US Naval vessel.
So here's the Navy coming in.
And we keep saying, oh, we're doing basic research.
And they say, yeah, but that's a Navy ship, as it legally is.
So there are all kinds of, I think, examples here where it need to be sort of clarified.
And my own feeling is, sure, it'd be fun to do research on other people's coastline and so on, not only from the kind of scientific interest of trying to help out these people.
Then they have the argument, as well as nobody in their country that can sort of interpret the data, which is certainly true.
So I think there's still plenty of ocean to look at, so I'm not too concerned at the moment.
What about the environmentalist impact?
I'm sorry, what do you mean?
Well, what obligation do oceanographers have to
to the environmentalist arguments which are developing very quickly and are involving oceanography as a discipline.
Well, what Sea pollution, for example.
Yeah, let me back up here for a moment.
I used to think I was an oceanographer, and as I've indicated to you, I had a very broad set of interests in terms of subject matter and so on.
But in recent years, I don't even call myself an oceanographer.
I call myself a marine environmental scientist because I've tried to sort of broaden out my interest.
And I think we have sort of major responsibilities in a way to
try and understand what the environment is and sort of identify some of the threats.
But this gets me off into another long sort of story here in that, as I see it, most of the conflicts that are around us today here
the battle between good and evil, in a sense.
And it's a conflict between those who want to, in effect, exploit the ocean.
And that means not only in terms of resources and so on, but even for waste disposal and so on, which becomes pollution here.
this on one side, and on the other, the environmental concern, which in its broadest sense is a very recent sort of thing.
I think it only goes back about 10 years or so.
How this conflict is going to be resolved is exceedingly difficult for me to see.
But many of them fall in this area.
And I think there are, again, some very real problems as to how those who would consider themselves as environmentally concerned private citizens and so on, as to how they can get

information and so on and i've had a number of sort of sad experiences of you know being asked can they get certain types of information and so on and i'd say oh yes and they then they say well who paid for this and i have to say well the navy or the atomic energy commission or the seattle power and light and they say oh well that's not what we want you know and yet they don't have
the money to support their own kind of programs.
And I've also been told that many of them have a great deal of difficulty of getting the kind of information that they think exists from state and federal agencies.
I'm sure they get fighted on the sort of Freedom of Information Act, but in many cases, they probably don't even know what it is they were to ask for.
So I think there is a very real sort of problem here of lack of support for the kind of environmentalist point of view.
And it's not always entirely rational, because if the scientific work is done adequately, it should stand up scrutiny.
I've had people, you know, just turn off completely because I have to say, well, yes, that was supported by some federal agency or something or other.
I mean, oh, that's tainted.
